description.plain: Leterrance Davis, better known as DJ Luke Nasty, was born in High Point NC. In high school he joined a four-man crew called the 336 Boyz. The group released two albums, 2010’s “I Told You So” and 2012’s “Full Cups and Empty Bottles”. Luke Nasty would then find Billboard chart success with his debut single “Might Be” peaking at #78 on the Hot 100 in 2016. His next single “OTW” would also chart, peaking at #71 on the Hot 100, and appear on his debut solo project Highway Music: Stuck in Traffic. He would end a successful 2016 with The Boom Boom Room EP, which features a remix of “OTW” featuring 2 Chainz. In 2018, he released his second album Cruise Control with features from DaBaby, Rotimi, and others.

description.plain:
Anderson Paak’s 2014 track “Might Be” is the basis for DJ Luke Nasty’s break-out single.

Originally Luke Nasty put “Might Be” out as a freestyle over Paak’s beat. Paak then reached out to Luke Nasty after his version started to become more popular on SoundCloud and together they reached an agreement that would allow Luke Nasty to use the track as his official single.

Producer Lo_Def originally made the beat for Paak by sampling Xscape’s 1995 cover of The Jones Girls' 1979 song “Who Can I Run To.”

For his version, Luke Nasty is rapping to a very specific female in his life about getting high and having sex.

I was just imaging her. She really got a body like J. Lo after she had enough. She heard it before I put the second verse on. Her and my people around me, they know who it’s about.
